{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775877816144,"sessionID":"ses_285703b89ffecpRDQILMzEYYNL","part":{"id":"prt_d7a90ff4d00165ymjrRcaQ02hF","messageID":"msg_d7a90fbf50019xqGrgZUGSXaTp","sessionID":"ses_285703b89ffecpRDQILMzEYYNL","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775877839716,"sessionID":"ses_285703b89ffecpRDQILMzEYYNL","part":{"id":"prt_d7a915b430018suxPlLZnaKJ13","messageID":"msg_d7a90fbf50019xqGrgZUGSXaTp","sessionID":"ses_285703b89ffecpRDQILMzEYYNL","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-6fe63f99817e4a18b0ecc5dfb8b7fae0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# AR-028 — SDK AgentRuntimeClient Proposal\n\n## Abstract\n\nThis proposal outlines the implementation of a Python SDK client for the AgentRuntime service, providing a high-level, type-safe interface for managing agents and their runtime sessions. The client will enable developers to programmatically create, configure, start, stop, and monitor AI agents within their Python applications.\n\n## Motivation\n\n### Problem Statement\n\nCurrently, developers interacting with the AgentRuntime service must:\n1. Manually construct HTTP requests\n2. Handle authentication and connection management\n3. Parse and validate JSON responses\n4. Implement retry logic and error handling\n5. Maintain data models and type definitions\n\nThis approach is error-prone, requires boilerplate code, and does not provide a developer-friendly API.\n\n### Proposed Solution\n\nCreate a dedicated Python SDK client that:\n1. Provides a clean, intuitive API for all AgentRuntime operations\n2. Handles authentication, retries, and error management automatically\n3. Offers type-safe data models using Pydantic\n4. Supports async/await for non-blocking operations\n5. Follows Python best practices and conventions\n\n## Goals\n\n### Primary Goals\n\n1. **Developer Experience** - Provide a simple, intuitive API that reduces boilerplate code\n2. **Type Safety** - Ensure compile-time type checking and runtime validation\n3. **Error Handling** - Provide clear, actionable error messages and exceptions\n4. **Performance** - Support high-throughput applications with async operations\n5. **Documentation** - Provide comprehensive documentation and examples\n\n### Secondary Goals\n\n1. **Extensibility** - Design for future feature additions\n2. **Testability** - Enable comprehensive unit and integration testing\n3. **Security** - Implement secure authentication and data handling\n4. **Compatibility** - Support Python 3.9+\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n1. **Support for Other Languages** - This AR is Python-specific only\n2. **Sync API** - Initial implementation will be async-only (can be added later)\n3. **Advanced Features** - Streaming, webhooks, and events are deferred to future ARs\n\n## Proposed Solution\n\n### Architecture\n\nThe SDK will consist of:\n\n1. **AgentRuntimeClient** - Main client class providing all operations\n2. **Data Models** - Pydantic models for type-safe data handling\n3. **Exception Hierarchy** - Comprehensive exception types\n4. **HTTP Client** - Wrapper around httpx for API communication\n5. **Configuration** - Support for client and agent configuration\n\n### API Design\n\n#### Agent Management\n\n```python\n# Create agent\nagent = await client.create_agent(\n    config=AgentConfig(\n        runtime_config=RuntimeConfig(type=\"llm\", model_id=\"gpt-4\", parameters={}),\n        capabilities=[\"chat\", \"code_generation\"]\n    ),\n    workspace_id=\"workspace-123\"\n)\n\n# Get agent\nagent = await client.get_agent(agent_id=\"agent-456\")\n\n# List agents\nagents = await client.list_agents(\n    workspace_id=\"workspace-123\",\n    status=AgentStatus.ACTIVE,\n    limit=50\n)\n\n# Update agent\nupdated_agent = await client.update_agent(\n    agent_id=\"agent-456\",\n    config=AgentConfig(...)\n)\n\n# Delete agent\nawait client.delete_agent(agent_id=\"agent-456\")\n```\n\n#### Runtime Operations\n\n```python\n# Start agent\nsession = await client.start_agent(\n    agent_id=\"agent-456\",\n    input_data={\"query\": \"Hello, world!\"}\n)\n\n# Get session status\nstatus = await client.get_session_status(session_id=\"session-789\")\n\n# List sessions\nsessions = await client.list_sessions(\n    agent_id=\"agent-456\",\n    status=SessionStatus.RUNNING\n)\n\n# Stop agent\nawait client.stop_agent(\n    session_id=\"session-789\",\n    graceful=True\n)\n```\n\n### Error Handling\n\n```python\ntry:\n    agent = await client.get_agent(agent_id=\"non-existent\")\nexcept AgentNotFoundError:\n    print(\"Agent not found\")\nexcept AuthenticationError:\n    print(\"Invalid credentials\")\nexcept ConnectionError:\n    print(\"Failed to connect to service\")\n```\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Use Existing HTTP Client Library\n\n**Pros:**\n- Leverages existing libraries like `requests` or `httpx`\n- Familiar to Python developers\n\n**Cons:**\n- Still requires boilerplate for each endpoint\n- No built-in error handling or retry logic\n- No type safety\n\n**Decision:** Rejected - Does not meet developer experience goals\n\n### Alternative 2: Generate SDK from OpenAPI Spec\n\n**Pros:**\n- Automatically synced with API changes\n- Less manual maintenance\n\n**Cons:**\n- Generated code may not follow Python best practices\n- Limited customization options\n- May have unclear error messages\n\n**Decision:** Rejected - Custom implementation provides better UX\n\n## Risks and Mitigations\n\n### Risk 1: API Changes During Development\n\n**Impact:** High\n**Probability:** Medium\n**Mitigation:**\n- Design for flexibility with versioned endpoints\n- Use semantic versioning\n- Maintain backward compatibility where possible\n\n### Risk 2: Performance Bottlenecks\n\n**Impact:** High\n**Probability:** Low\n**Mitigation:**\n- Use async/await for non-blocking operations\n- Implement connection pooling\n- Add configurable timeouts and retry logic\n- Profile and optimize hot paths\n\n### Risk 3: Complexity Explosion\n\n**Impact:** Medium\n**Probability:** Medium\n**Mitigation:**\n- Keep API surface minimal and focused\n- Defer advanced features to future ARs\n- Provide clear documentation and examples\n- Implement comprehensive tests\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n1. **API Completeness** - All AgentRuntime endpoints are accessible via the SDK\n2. **Type Safety** - 100% of public API is fully typed\n3. **Test Coverage** - >90% code coverage with unit and integration tests\n4. **Documentation** - All public methods documented with examples\n5. **Performance** - <100ms median latency for simple operations\n6. **Developer Satisfaction** - Positive feedback from early adopters\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Core Infrastructure (Week 1-2)\n- [ ] Set up project structure\n- [ ] Implement base HTTP client\n- [ ] Create data models\n- [ ] Implement exception hierarchy\n\n### Phase 2: Agent Management (Week 3-4)\n- [ ] Implement CRUD operations for agents\n- [ ] Add filtering and pagination\n- [ ] Write unit tests\n\n### Phase 3: Runtime Operations (Week 5-6)\n- [ ] Implement session management\n- [ ] Add start/stop operations\n- [ ] Write unit tests\n\n### Phase 4: Testing and Documentation (Week 7-8)\n- [ ] Write integration tests\n- [ ] Create comprehensive documentation\n- [ ] Add usage examples\n- [ ] Performance testing and optimization\n\n### Phase 5: Review and Release (Week 9-10)\n- [ ] Code review\n- [ ] Bug fixes\n- [ ] Release preparation\n- [ ] Documentation review\n\n## Dependencies\n\n### External Dependencies\n\n- `httpx` >= 0.24.0 - HTTP client\n- `pydantic` >= 2.0.0 - Data validation\n- `typing-extensions` >= 4.0.0 - Type hints\n\n### Internal Dependencies\n\n- python-sdk (base SDK infrastructure)\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. **Retry Strategy** - Should we implement exponential backoff with jitter?\n2. **Caching** - Should we cache agent or session data?\n3. **Rate Limiting** - Should we implement client-side rate limiting?\n4. **Metrics** - What metrics should be exposed?\n\n## Timeline\n\nEstimated completion: 10 weeks\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe AgentRuntimeClient will significantly improve the developer experience for interacting with the AgentRuntime service, providing a clean, type-safe, and efficient API. By following Python best practices and implementing comprehensive testing and documentation, we can ensure high-quality, maintainable code that serves as a foundation for future enhancements.","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-028/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-028/proposal.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-028/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775877839710,"end":1775877839714}}}}
